SIMPLE: lithodomus
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lithodomus
<hw>Li*thod"o*mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See
<er>Lithodome</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of elongated
bivalve shells, allied to the mussels, and remarkable for their ability
to bore holes for shelter, in solid limestone, shells, etc. Called also
<altname>Lithophagus</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ These holes are at first very small and shallow, but are
enlarged with the growth of the shell, sometimes becoming two or three
inches deep and nearly an inch diameter.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lithofellic</ent>⟦br⟧
